íźźŔ Title: Type signatures
Path: The infix type operators
Content:
``:``
 - Read as 
``is type of``
``->``
 - Read as "becomes type of" or as 
``to type of``
 in custom commands in the return type position
óŔcarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/lang-guide/chapters/types/type_signatures.mdŔ@dd5f543aa693d0b786ed7d2e5bc5aa1315e00af17f1b75e56c92dcec789e3503ĮType signaturesĎŔ'Nushell constructs with type signaturesŕďThere are several syntactic forms that can have type signatures:
Variable declarations
Parameter declarations in custom commands and closures
Input and Return type declarations for custom commands
The following code snippets illustrates these kinds of type signatures:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# Variable declaration
let x: int = 9

# Parameter declaration in custom commands
def my-command [x: int, y: string] { }

# Parameter declaration in closures
do {|nums : list<int>| $nums | describe} [ 1 2 3 ]

# Input and Return type declaration on a custom command
def my-filter []: nothing -> list { }

# Multiple Input/Return type signatures on a custom command
def my-filter []: [
  nothing -> list
  range -> list
] { }

```
For a further discussion on custom command signatures please refer to: 
[link: /book/custom_commands.html] Custom Commands

And also: 
[link: /book/command_signature.html] Command Signature
íźźŕŠTitle: Type signatures
Path: Nushell constructs with type signatures
Content:
There are several syntactic forms that can have type signatures:
Variable declarations
Parameter declarations in custom commands and closures
Input and Return type declarations for custom commands
The following code snippets illustrates these kinds of type signatures:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# Variable declaration
let x: int = 9

# Parameter declaration in custom commands
def my-command [x: int, y: string] { }

# Parameter declaration in closures
do {|nums : list<int>| $nums | describe} [ 1 2 3 ]

# Input and Return type declaration on a custom command
def my-filter []: nothing -> list { }

# Multiple Input/Return type signatures on a custom command
def my-filter []: [
  nothing -> list
  range -> list
] { }

```
For a further discussion on custom command signatures please refer to: 
[link: /book/custom_commands.html] Custom Commands

And also: 
[link: /book/command_signature.html] Command Signature
óŔcarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/lang-guide/chapters/types/type_signatures.mdŔ@612906b8a8ebfd67f696144d746f20990dcfb3ed6f194f03862d867b8b8e0c92ĮType signaturesĎłKinds of type signaturesŔ©There are 3 forms of valid type signatures in Nu:
Basic: E.g. 
``int``
, 
``bool``
, 
``string``
, etc.
Compound:
``list<string>``
,

``record<type: int, bar: string>``
íźźŔŤTitle: Type signatures
Path: Kinds of type signatures
Content:
There are 3 forms of valid type signatures in Nu:
Basic: E.g. 
``int``
, 
``bool``
, 
``string``
, etc.
Compound:
``list<string>``
,

``record<type: int, bar: string>``
óŔcarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/lang-guide/chapters/types/type_signatures.mdŔ@c4703bf080a9b50e44ceb9d30f12bb5f994e1e4e8ac90a1b0ae63d02c7c30085ĮType signaturesĎŔ#Custom command parameters and flagsŔ≥This section does not enumerate all of the various ways to create parameters

and flags to custom commands. Here we only discuss the type annotation to both

types of parameters.
íźźŔżTitle: Type signatures
Path: Custom command parameters and flags
Content:
This section does not enumerate all of the various ways to create parameters

and flags to custom commands. Here we only discuss the type annotation to both

types of parameters.
óŔcarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/lang-guide/chapters/types/type_signatures.mdŔ@fcd17d0bf8a66ecc98fec51dac018e9bc77f15530422c9227eeb77aab46702c7ĮType signaturesĎ™ParametersŕĎIf a parameter to a custom command or a closure is type-annotated, then it will

have the 
``:``
 operator after the name followed by the type signature

and before any default value.
E.g., a fully articulated parameter with a type annotation:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
def fully [some?: int = 9] { $some }

```
The above command has an optional parameter of type 
``int``
 with a default value of 9.
íźźŕ¬Title: Type signatures
Path: Parameters
Content:
If a parameter to a custom command or a closure is type-annotated, then it will

have the 
``:``
 operator after the name followed by the type signature

and before any default value.
E.g., a fully articulated parameter with a type annotation:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
def fully [some?: int = 9] { $some }

```
The above command has an optional parameter of type 
``int``
 with a default value of 9.
óŔcarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/lang-guide/chapters/types/type_signatures.mdŔ@3562ff9682a945b47f744a700bf9a1298e62c7f1356be32e9ec5338fcd40bf7dĮType signaturesĎĽType annotations for flags.ŕ)If a flag has a type annotation, then it expects an argument matching that type

which can be 
``any``
 for all types. If the type is missing, then the flag is assumed

to be either present or not present at the call site.
Thus, within the body of the command, the type of that flag's named variable

binding will be 
``bool``
 and its value will be 
``true``
 if the flag is present

and 
``false``
 if not present.
You cannot use the 
``bool``
 type as a flag annotation as that is the same

as the the existence or not of the occurrence of the flag.
íźźŕkTitle: Type signatures
Path: Type annotations for flags.
Content:
If a flag has a type annotation, then it expects an argument matching that type

which can be 
``any``
 for all types. If the type is missing, then the flag is assumed

to be either present or not present at the call site.
Thus, within the body of the command, the type of that flag's named variable

binding will be 
``bool``
 and its value will be 
``true``
 if the flag is present

and 
``false``
 if not present.
You cannot use the 
``bool``
 type as a flag annotation as that is the same

as the the existence or not of the occurrence of the flag.
